            <div>
                <opener>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I have just time to thank you for y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> favor of Jan.
                        10<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. &amp; to say it will be needless to bustle
                        y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>self ab<hi rend="superscript">t</hi> the
                    macleans; except there be something very remarkable.</p>
                <p>If you can give me <bibl type="authorial">
                        <title ref="bi0103">the oct<hi rend="superscript">vo</hi> Edition of abercrombie</title>
                    </bibl> I
                    shall be glad &amp; will pay you for that &amp; <bibl type="authorial">
                        <title ref="bi0064">magazines</title>
                    </bibl>: but why do they persist in
                    sending them.</p>
                <p>About 130 pages of my 3<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> edition q<hi rend="superscript">to</hi> are printed.<note type="editorial">A reference to
                        the third edition of Pennant's <bibl type="editorial">
                            <title ref="bi0004">
                                Tour in Scotland 1769</title> (Warrington: 1774)</bibl>.</note> The
                    other will be soon ready I hope. Be so good as to read seal, &amp; forward my
                    letter to M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Low.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>yrs in vast hurry</salute>
                    <signed>
                        <persName ref="pe0232">T. Pennant</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <dateline>Jan. 18<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. 1774.</dateline>

                <postscript>
                    <p>Pray how much english money is a scotch mark</p>
                    <p>
                        <handShift/>1.1 â…“</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
